06276nam a22008535i 9781477318416DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20212019txu    fo  d z      eng d  a2018043826  a97814773184167 a10.7560/3184092doi  a(DE-B1597)588045  a(OCoLC)1269268430  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX00aF1219.56.C7552bF55 2019 4aF1219.56.C7552bF55 2019 7aART0000002bisacsh04a972/.0222304aThe Florentine Codex :bAn Encyclopedia of the Nahua World in Sixteenth-Century Mexico /ced. by Kevin Trerraciano, Jeanette Favrot Peterson. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©2019  a1 online resource (241 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface and Acknowledgments -- tIntroduction: An Encyclopedia of Nahua Culture: Context and Content -- tPart I THE ART OF TRANSLATION -- tChapter 1 Images in Translation: A Codex “Muy Historiado” -- tChapter 2 On the Reception of the Florentine Codex: The First Italian Translation -- tChapter 3 Reading between the Lines of Book 12 -- tChapter 4 The Art of War, the Working Class, and Snowfall: Reflections on the Assimilation of Western Aesthetics -- tPart II LORDS ROYAL AND SACRED -- tChapter 5 Surviving Conquest: Depicting Aztec Deities in Sahagún’s Historia -- tChapter 6 Fashioning Conceptual Categories in the Florentine Codex: Old-World and Indigenous Foundations for the Rulers and the Gods -- tChapter 7 Teotl and Diablo: Indigenous and Christian Conceptions of Gods and Devils in the Florentine Codex -- tPart III ORDERING THE COSMOS -- tChapter 8 Ecology and Leadership: Pantitlan and Other Erratic Phenomena -- tChapter 9 Bundling Natural History: Tlaquimilolli, Folk Biology, and Book 11 -- tChapter 10 Powerful Words and Eloquent Images -- tPart IV SOCIAL DISCOURSE AND DEVIANCE -- tChapter 11 Rhetoric as Acculturation: The Anomalous Book 6 -- tChapter 12 Flowers and Speech in Discourses on Deviance in Book 10 -- tChapter 13 Parts of the Body Order and Disorder -- tBibliography -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the sixteenth century, the Franciscan friar Bernardino de Sahagún and a team of indigenous grammarians, scribes, and painters completed decades of work on an extraordinary encyclopedic project titled General History of the Things of New Spain, known as the Florentine Codex (1575–1577). Now housed in the Biblioteca Medicea Laurenziana in Florence and bound in three lavishly illustrated volumes, the codex is a remarkable product of cultural exchange in the early Americas. In this edited volume, experts from multiple disciplines analyze the manuscript’s bilingual texts and more than 2,000 painted images and offer fascinating, new insights on its twelve books. The contributors examine the “three texts” of the codex—the original Nahuatl, its translation into Spanish, and its painted images. Together, these constitute complementary, as well as conflicting, voices of an extended dialogue that occurred in and around Mexico City. The volume chapters address a range of subjects, from Nahua sacred beliefs, moral discourse, and natural history to the Florentine artists’ models and the manuscript’s reception in Europe. The Florentine Codex ultimately yields new perspectives on the Nahua world several decades after the fall of the Aztec empire.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aAztecsxHistoryy16th century. 0aManuscripts, Mexican. 0aManuscripts, Nahuatl. 7aART / General.2bisacsh1 aBaird, Ellen T., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBassett, Molly H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBoone, Elizabeth Hill, econtributor.4ctb4https